{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781458697164,"sessionID":"ses_138ce4b7fffegpX9L4tC4pzcvD","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_00_ayHZgMQsdIyjIlx29PiH2673","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"include":"*.md","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills","pattern":"mcp-magicpath|magicpath-ai"},"output":"Found 18 matches\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-prompt/changelog/v2.2.0.0.md:\n  Line 1: This release adds a design-generation prompt pattern so sk-prompt serves the framework's design-generation tools, not just text tasks. The skill was a generic text-prompt engine: seven frameworks, DEPTH, CLEAR, and three format guides. None of it knew how to write a brief for `mcp-magicpath` canvas authoring or `mcp-open-design` `start_run`, where a generic brief produces the median AI look the house design skill exists to resist. A new reference plus router wiring closes that gap without a new pipeline.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-prompt/changelog/v2.3.0.0.md:\n  Line 1: This release narrows the design-generation prompt pattern to a single tool. The `mcp-magicpath` skill is removed, so `references/design_generation_patterns.md` no longer documents MagicPath canvas authoring and the `DESIGN_GEN` router no longer keys on \"magicpath\". The Open Design `start_run` usecase, the grounded anti-default brief, the String Seed of Thought variation technique, and the discovery-form pre-answer are unchanged.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-open-design/changelog/v1.2.0.0.md:\n  Line 2: title: \"mcp-open-design v1.2.0.0 - Retire the mcp-magicpath sibling reference\"\n\n  Line 5: # v1.2.0.0 - Retire the mcp-magicpath sibling reference\n\n  Line 9: The `mcp-magicpath` skill is removed now that this skill drives the installed Open Design app from the terminal and covers the local design-generation usecase. This release drops the now-dead `mcp-magicpath` sibling reference so the related-skill set and graph edges point only at live skills. There is no change to the Open Design transport, the tool surface, or the gating policy.\n\n  Line 17: - SKILL.md removes the `mcp-magicpath` related-skill bullet and the magicpath mention in the Section 8 related-skills prose.\n\n  Line 18: - README drops the `mcp-magicpath` row from the Related Skills table.\n\n  Line 19: - `graph-metadata.json` removes the `mcp-magicpath` siblings edge and removes it from `manual.related_to`. The `mcp-figma` sibling edge and the `sk-interface-design` design-judgment dependency are unchanged.\n\n  Line 25: - This is a reference-hygiene release tied to the `mcp-magicpath` deprecation. The Open Design generation flow, the multi-turn `start_run` plus discovery-form behavior corrected in v1.1.0.0, and every verb and gate are unchanged.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-interface-design/changelog/v1.3.0.0.md:\n  Line 9: The sibling `mcp-magicpath` skill is retired now that `mcp-open-design` drives the installed Open Design app from the terminal, so the shared Claude Design parity protocol re-centers on a single generation transport. The protocol's two members are now this skill (the judgment) and `mcp-open-design` (the Open Design terminal transport). The fidelity check moves off the MagicPath hosted-canvas mechanism (`previewImageUrl` plus the `design_fidelity.py` helper) onto Open Design's real `previewUrl`: the rendered design from a completed multi-turn run, with the written files read through `get_artifact`. The loop, the grounding, the reuse-before-generate discipline, the quality floor, and the anti-default mandate are all unchanged.\n\n  Line 17: - The protocol description and the two-member framing drop `mcp-magicpath`. The judgment stays here and the transport is `mcp-open-design`.\n\n  Line 25: - SKILL.md drops the `mcp-magicpath` related-skill line and the magicpath mention in the parity reference summary. Version moves to 1.3.0.\n\n  Line 31: - `graph-metadata.json` drops the `mcp-magicpath` `prerequisite_for` edge and removes it from `related_to`. The `mcp-open-design` prerequisite edge stays.\n\n  Line 39: | Parity members | sk-interface-design, mcp-magicpath, mcp-open-design | sk-interface-design, mcp-open-design |\n\n  Line 50: - Historical changelog entries that mention `mcp-magicpath` stay as record. The `mcp-magicpath` skill is removed in the same packet that ships this release.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-interface-design/changelog/v1.0.0.0.md:\n  Line 9: This initial release ships `sk-interface-design` as a data-backed judgment skill that also shares a Claude Design parity loop with `mcp-magicpath`, while keeping it lean and anti-default. It vendors Anthropic's frontend-design skill - a SKILL.md plus one design-principles reference, all guidance and no data - and builds on that baseline with design data, an optional search, additional references, and the shared parity protocol. The design process and the anti-default mandate come from the upstream skill and are preserved unchanged.\n\n  Line 42: - `graph-metadata.json` - trigger phrases (color palette, font pairing, design tokens, ux checklist) and key_files for the data, search, and parity surfaces; the `enhances sk-code` and `prerequisite_for mcp-magicpath` edges set.\n\n  Line 53: | Iteration | Private, in-thinking only | The parity loop adds a render fidelity check (via mcp-magicpath `previewImageUrl`) |\n","metadata":{"matches":18,"truncated":false},"title":"mcp-magicpath|magicpath-ai","time":{"start":1781458697102,"end":1781458697163}},"id":"prt_ec73679240012GBXS3gis31NLQ","sessionID":"ses_138ce4b7fffegpX9L4tC4pzcvD","messageID":"msg_ec7365f4f001AzA1LfirTLtjLv"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781458697909,"sessionID":"ses_138ce4b7fffegpX9L4tC4pzcvD","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_01_18GvovIN2teOj4geZEm31952","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"include":"*.md","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-open-design","pattern":"one.shot|single call|single .* produce"},"output":"Found 12 matches\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-open-design/SKILL.md:\n  Line 213: Generation is **multi-turn, not one-shot**. A single `start_run` (MCP) or `od run start` (CLI) fires **turn 1 only**, which returns a GenUI discovery question-form (the inner agent asking about fidelity, data, and behaviour, with recommended defaults) and ends `awaiting_input` with **zero files**. A run that stops here produces no design.\n\n  Line 255: 5. **NEVER claim a single `start_run` or `od run start` produced a finished, visible design.** Turn 1 only returns the discovery form. A design exists only after the form is answered and the build run writes files. Never present `od artifacts create` as a way to create a rendered design.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-open-design/README.md:\n  Line 158: A: Generation is multi-turn, not one-shot. A single `start_run` or `od run start` fires turn 1 only, which returns a GenUI discovery question-form and zero files, ending `awaiting_input`. You answer that form with `od ui respond` (or a follow-up message like \"use the recommended defaults\"), and that is what fires the build run that writes the design files and gives the project a `previewUrl`. Do not use `od artifacts create` to \"make a design\": it only adds a single file and never renders one.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-open-design/changelog/v1.1.0.0.md:\n  Line 9: Corrects the skill to the live-verified reality of how Open Design generates designs. The v1.0.0 release was built from a reverse-engineering pass and described generation as a one-shot `start_run`. A live generation test this session proved that generation is multi-turn, and that `od artifacts create` only adds a file rather than creating a rendered design. This release brings every doc in line with what was proven live, adds the `od run` verb family and the HTTP API surface, and preserves everything the prior release got right.\n\n  Line 15: ### Corrected: generation is multi-turn, not one-shot\n\n  Line 17: The load-bearing fix. A single `start_run` (MCP) or `od run start` (CLI) fires turn 1 only, which returns a GenUI discovery question-form and ends `awaiting_input` with zero files. The design is built only after the form is answered with `od ui respond` (or a follow-up message), which fires the build run that writes `index.html` and gives the project an `entryFile` and a `previewUrl`. Live proof this session: turn 1 produced a question-form with zero files, and after it was answered a build run wrote a 26 KB `index.html` and the project rendered with a `previewUrl`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:\n  Line 53: `create_artifact` and the CLI `od artifacts create` only **add a single file** to a project. They do NOT spawn a run, do NOT produce a rendered design, and do NOT update the project preview. The visible-design path is the multi-turn `start_run` flow above, never an artifact write. **[CONFIRMED - live-verified this session]**\n\n  Line 103: Generation is **multi-turn, not one-shot**. The headless loop runs over the MCP tools (plus `od ui` to answer the form) once wired:\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-open-design/feature_catalog/04--runs/headless-runs.md:\n  Line 21: Generation is multi-turn, not one-shot. Turn 1 returns a discovery question-form with zero files, and the design is built only after that form is answered. Generation and the other write verbs are the powerful half of the skill, so every one of them is a stop-and-confirm point. A run is described to the user with its effect and its rollback before it is launched, and a destructive verb needs more than that.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-open-design/references/od_cli_reference.md:\n  Line 171: A visible, rendered design is produced by a **multi-turn** flow, never a single call. **[CONFIRMED - live-verified this session]**\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-open-design/manual_testing_playbook/03--gated-runs/gated-verb-confirm.md:\n  Line 18: The run direction is the powerful half of the skill, and a mutating verb that fires without confirmation is the worst failure mode. The negative control is the heart of this scenario: an unconfirmed mutating call, or a destructive verb without `confirm:true`, must be refused. Without that guard, generation and deletion become unsafe. The second risk this scenario guards is the one-shot illusion: a single `start_run` or `od run start` returns only a discovery form with zero files, so claiming it produced a finished design (or using `od artifacts create` as a stand-in) is a correctness failure.\n\n  Line 32: - Pass/fail: PASS if the confirmed run proceeded through the multi-turn flow (form answered, build wrote files, project has a `previewUrl`) AND the unconfirmed control was refused. FAIL if any mutating verb ran without confirmation OR a destructive verb ran without confirm:true OR a single turn-1 call was claimed to produce a finished design\n","metadata":{"matches":12,"truncated":false},"title":"one.shot|single call|single .* produce","time":{"start":1781458697899,"end":1781458697908}},"id":"prt_ec7367bd9001213mCq9kuNeg0O","sessionID":"ses_138ce4b7fffegpX9L4tC4pzcvD","messageID":"msg_ec7365f4f001AzA1LfirTLtjLv"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781458698539,"sessionID":"ses_138ce4b7fffegpX9L4tC4pzcvD","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_02_B1gqW7kBfSu1ntWYdc6T7677","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"include":"*.md","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-open-design","pattern":"v1\\.1\\.0"},"output":"Found 3 matches\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-open-design/changelog/v1.1.0.0.md:\n  Line 2: title: \"mcp-open-design v1.1.0.0 - Generation Flow Correction\"\n\n  Line 5: # v1.1.0.0 - Generation Flow Correction\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-open-design/changelog/v1.2.0.0.md:\n  Line 25: - This is a reference-hygiene release tied to the `mcp-magicpath` deprecation. The Open Design generation flow, the multi-turn `start_run` plus discovery-form behavior corrected in v1.1.0.0, and every verb and gate are unchanged.\n","metadata":{"matches":3,"truncated":false},"title":"v1\\.1\\.0","time":{"start":1781458698516,"end":1781458698538}},"id":"prt_ec7367ef20010HLwWV71tcE2Nl","sessionID":"ses_138ce4b7fffegpX9L4tC4pzcvD","messageID":"msg_ec7365f4f001AzA1LfirTLtjLv"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1781458698865,"sessionID":"ses_138ce4b7fffegpX9L4tC4pzcvD","part":{"id":"prt_ec736826f001KiM8avpYgZKCHd","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"c79d0876eac35fe9d9b114abdb754a116fc92e09","messageID":"msg_ec7365f4f001AzA1LfirTLtjLv","sessionID":"ses_138ce4b7fffegpX9L4tC4pzcvD","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":159083,"input":3815,"output":305,"reasoning":339,"cache":{"write":0,"read":154624}},"cost":0.002780317}}
